description:
Bug 38131: ajc needs -d option. I am using ajc 1.1rc1. This is a regression since rc1 and a deviation from javac. I am guessing this may have something to do with a change in the underlying Eclipse compiler.

To reproduce the issue:
1. Create a class in a subpackage, such as:
   package subpackage;

   public class Test {
       public static void main(String[] args) {
           System.out.println("Hello");
       }
   }

2. Compile the class using the following command: ajc subpackage\Test.java

Observed Behavior:
- The compiled Test.class file is put in the subpackage\subpackage directory, which is unexpected.
- Running the java command results in an exception:
   Exception in thread "main" java.lang.NoClassDefFoundError: subpackage/Test

Expected Behavior:
- The compiled Test.class file should be put in the subpackage directory and not the subpackage\subpackage directory.

Steps to Reproduce:
- Compile the class again using one of the following commands to fix the problem: ajc -d . subpackage\Test.java
